A push is a specific behavior that a customer exhibits when they are trying to get a job done. It is a specific action that they take to make progress toward their goal. In the context of jtbd, a push is a key part of understanding the customer's motivations and behaviors. By identifying the pushes that customers exhibit, businesses can design products and services that meet their needs and help them get the job done. For example, a customer may push to buy a new smartphone because their old one is slow and they need a better camera. In this case, the push is the customer's desire for a better phone, and the business can design a product that meets that need. Pushes can be thought of as the "why" behind the customer's behavior. Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!-- Project Information -->
  <groupId>com.example</groupId>
  <artifactId>myproject</artifactId>
  <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  <packaging>jar</packaging>

  <!-- Project Name and Description -->
  <name>My Project</name>
  <description>This is my project.</description>

  <!-- Project Properties -->
  <properties>
    <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
    <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
    <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
  </properties>

  <!-- Project Dependencies -->
  <dependencies>
    <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
  </dependencies>

  <!-- Project Build Settings -->
  <build>
    <plugins>
      <plugin>
        <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
        <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
        <version>3.8.1</version>
        <configuration>
          <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
          <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
        </configuration>
      </plugin>
    </plugins>
  </build>
</project>
